            <div n="1" xml:lang="eng">
                <head>
                    <hi rendition="#k">Diversities of Savage Races.</hi>
                </head>
                <p>&#x2014;The Northern desert<lb break="yes"/>of <placeName key="afrika"
                        >Africa</placeName> divides two races of men who belong, origi-<lb
                        break="no"/>nally, to the same part of the globe, and whose unre-<lb
                        break="no"/>conciled discord appears as ancient as the mythus of<lb
                        break="yes"/>
                    <persName key="osiris">Osiris</persName> and <persName key="typhon"
                        >Typhon</persName>. North of the <placeName key="atlas">Atlas</placeName>
                    there dwell<lb break="yes"/>nations with long and straight hair, of sallow
                        complex-<lb break="no"/>ion, and Caucasian features. On the South of the
                        Sene-<lb break="no"/>gal, towards Soudan, live hordes of Negroes in many<lb
                        break="yes"/>different stages of civilization. In Central <placeName
                        key="asien">Asia</placeName>, the<lb break="yes"/>Mongolian steppe divides
                    Siberian barbarism from the<lb break="yes"/>ancient civilization of the
                    peninsula of India. The<lb break="yes"/>
                    <placeName key="suedamerika">South American</placeName> steppes form the
                    boundary of a partial<lb break="yes"/>European cultivation. To the North,
                    between the<lb break="yes"/>mountains of Venezuela and the Caribbean sea, we
                        find<lb break="yes"/>commercial cities, neat villages, and carefully
                        cultivated<lb break="yes"/>fields. Even the love of art and scientific
                    culture, to-<lb break="no"/>gether with the noble desire of civil freedom, have
                        long<lb break="yes"/>been awakened there. Towards the South, the steppe<lb
                        break="yes"/>terminates in a savage wilderness. Forests, the<lb break="yes"
                    />growth of thousands of years, fill, with their impene-<lb break="no"/>trable
                    fastnesses, the humid regions between the Ori-<lb break="no"/>noco and
                        <placeName key="amazonas">the Amazons</placeName>. Massive leaden-colored
                        granite<lb break="yes"/>rocks narrow the bed of the foaming rivers.
                        Mountains<lb break="yes"/>and forests resound with the thunder of the
                        falling<lb break="yes"/>waters, with the roar of the tiger-like jaguar, and
                        with<lb break="yes"/>the melancholy rain, announcing the bowlings of the<lb
                        break="yes"/>bearded apes. Where a sand-bank is left dry by the<lb
                        break="yes"/>shallow current, the unwieldy crocodiles lie, with open<lb
                        break="yes"/>jaws, as motionless as pieces of rock, and often covered<lb
                        break="yes"/>with birds. The boa serpent, his body marked like a<lb
                        break="yes"/>chess-board, coiled up, his tail wound round the branch<lb
                        break="yes"/>of a tree, lies lurking on the bank, secure of his prey;<lb
                        break="yes"/>he marks the young bull, or some feebler inhabitant of<lb
                        break="yes"/>the forest, as it fords the stream, and swiftly uncoiling,<lb
                        break="yes"/>seizes the victim, and covering it with mucus, forces it<lb
                        break="yes"/>laboriously down his swelling throat. In the midst of<lb
                        break="yes"/>this grand and savage nature live many tribes of men,<lb
                        break="yes"/>isolated from each other by the extraordinary diversity<lb
                        break="yes"/>of their languages: some are nomadic, wholly unacquainted<lb
                        break="yes"/>with agriculture, and using ants, gums, and earth as food.<lb
                        break="yes"/>These, as the Otomacs and Jarures, seem a kind of outcasts<lb
                        break="yes"/>from humanity; others, like the Maquiritares and Ma-<lb
                        break="no"/>cos, are settled, more intelligent, and of milder man-<lb
                        break="no"/>ners, and live on fruits which they have themselves<lb
                        break="yes"/>reared. Large spaces between the Cassiquiare and the<lb
                        break="yes"/>
                    <placeName key="atabapo">Atabapo</placeName> are only inhabited by the tapir and
                    the social<lb break="yes"/>apes, and are wholly destitute of human beings.
                        Figures<lb break="yes"/>graven on the rocks show that even these deserts
                        were<lb break="yes"/>once the seat of some degree of intellectual
                        cultivation.<lb break="yes"/>They bear witness to the changeful destinies of
                    man, as<lb break="yes"/>do the unequally developed flexible languages; which<lb
                        break="yes"/>latter belong to the oldest and most imperishable class of<lb
                        break="yes"/>historic memorials. But as in the steppe tigers and<lb
                        break="yes"/>crocodiles fight with horses and cattle, so in the forests<lb
                        break="yes"/>on its borders, in the wildernesses of Guiana, man is ever<lb
                        break="yes"/>armed against man. Some tribes drink with unna-<lb break="no"
                    />tural thirst the blood of their enemies; others ap-<lb break="no"/>parently
                    weaponless, and yet prepared for murder,<lb break="yes"/>kill with a poisoned
                    thumb-nail. The weaker hordes,<lb break="yes"/>when they have to pass along the
                    sandy margin of the<lb break="yes"/>rivers, carefully efface with their hands
                    the traces of<lb break="yes"/>their timid footsteps. Thus man, in the lowest
                        stage<lb break="yes"/>of almost animal rudeness, as well as amidst the
                        ap-<lb break="no"/>parent brilliancy of our higher cultivation, prepares<lb
                        break="yes"/>for himself and his fellow-men increased toil and<lb
                        break="yes"/>danger. The traveller wandering over the wide globe<lb
                        break="yes"/>by sea and land, as well as the historic inquirer search-<lb
                        break="no"/>ing the records of past ages, finds everywhere the uni-<lb
                        break="no"/>form and saddening spectacle of man at variance with<lb
                        break="yes"/>man. He, therefore, who, amidst the unreconciled dis-<lb
                        break="no"/>cord of nations, seeks for intellectual calm, gladly turns<lb
                        break="yes"/>to contemplate the silent life of vegetation, and the<lb
                        break="yes"/>hidden activities of forces and powers operating in the<lb
                        break="yes"/>sanctuaries of nature; or, obedient to the inborn im-<lb
                        break="no"/>pulse which for thousands of years has glowed in the<lb
                        break="yes"/>human breast, gazes upwards in meditative contempla-<lb
                        break="no"/>tion on those celestial orbs, which are ever pursuing in<lb
                        break="yes"/>undisturbed harmony their ancient and unchanging<lb break="yes"
                    />course. &#x2014; <hi rendition="#i">
                        <persName key="humboldt_av">Humboldt</persName>&#x2019;s Aspects of
                        Nature.</hi>
                </p>
            </div>
